tThe Global, Imperial Metropolis: Ideas from 1873 Berlin -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCould the concepts of »metropolitanism« and »thick space« aid our understanding of historical and contemporary urban change? Essays by scholars from both sides of the Atlantic provide interdisciplinary approaches to the complex dynamics of large-scale urbanization. The book opens with conceptual questions regarding the development of metropoles and metropolitan studies. The following sections provide analyses of the social, environmental, and cultural dimensions of metropolitan spaces from both a theoretical and an empirical perspective, such as the role of planning and urban parks, the impact of ethnic diversity and segregation, the place of cinematic visions or the centrality of infrastructures and architecture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 4aMedia. 4aMetropolitanism. 4aSociology. 4aSpace. 4aTheory of Urban Studies. 4aUrban Space. 4aUrban Studies. 4aUrbanity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aMedia.  aMetropolitanism.  aSociology.  aSpace.  aTheory of Urban Studies.  aUrban Space.  aUrban Studies.  aUrbanity.1 aBender, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrantz, Dorothee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrantz, Dorothee, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDisko, Sasha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDisko, Sasha, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDümpelmann, Sonja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarías, Ignacio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrahm, L